<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-107-205 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 085 567</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  July 11 1991 v39 n13 p109(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DSOs sport better performance, intuitive interfaces. (digitalstorage oscilloscopes) (Test andamp; Measurement Update) (tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Novellino, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Digital storage oscilloscopes (DSO) are increasingly becomingcharacterized by improved performance and intuitive interfaces.andO;DSO manufacturers must balance the need to make DSOs easier to usewith customers' need for more features.andP;  The features of many newDSOs include frequency-domain functions, improvedtransient-capture capability, and larger acquisition memories.andO;The amount of available DSOs has almost doubled between Jun 1988and Jul 1991, and sales of DSOs are greater than sales of analogversions in terms of dollar volume per year.andP;  One trend in DSOs isincreasing record lengths, which allow DSOs to maintain theirmaximum sampling rate at slower time-base settings, allow users tofocus in on part of a displayed waveform without sacrificingdetail, and allow users to utilize pre-trigger recording.andP;  Twopossible types of DSO users are 'engineering and up' groups, whichconsist of users working in research and design, and 'engineeringand down' groups, which consist of engineering laboratory workersand technicians.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Functional CapabilitiesPerformanceUser InterfaceUser ClassificationOscilloscopesTutorial.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>